# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: memory-safety
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] In computer security and programming, an **out-of-bounds read** is a software anomaly where a program, while reading data from a buffer, reads outside of the buffer's boundary from adjacent memory.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] This is a special case of violation of memory safety and is a form of data confidentiality violation (see CIA triad).
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] A **buffer over-read** and **buffer under-read** are special cases of out-of-bounds reads.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] Out-of-bounds reads are the basis of many software vulnerabilities.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] In some cases, they can be maliciously exploited to access privileged information.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] For example, they can sometimes be triggered, as in the Heartbleed bug, by maliciously crafted inputs that are designed to exploit a lack of bounds checking to read inaccessible parts of memory.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] At other times, out-of-bounds reads can result in other erratic program behavior, including memory access errors (including invalid page faults), incorrect results, or crashes.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] For example, the widespread IT outages in 2024 were caused by an out-of-bounds memory error in cybersecurity software developed by CrowdStrike.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] Bounds checking, sandboxing, static analysis, using memory safe programming languages, and program verification can prevent buffer over-reads, while techniques such as fuzz testing can help detect them.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] Mitre Corporation (MITRE) categorizes out-of-bounds reads under Common Weakness Enumeration CWE-125, with child categories CWE-126 (buffer over-read) and CWE-127 (buffer under-read).
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] MITRE lists the corresponding attack pattern under Common Attack Pattern Enumeration and Classification "CAPEC-540: Overread Buffers." This attack is listed at a low likelihood of attack, but a high typical severity if an attack does occur.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] MITRE recommends that buffer over-reads can be effectively detected with static analysis (more specifically, static application security testing).
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] It recommends dynamic analysis (such as AddressSanitizer) as having moderate effectiveness at detection.
[src:memory-safety/buffer-over-read] Fuzzing is also listed as a highly effective detection method.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Dangling pointers arise during object destruction, when an object that is pointed to by a given pointer is deleted or deallocated, without modifying the value of that said pointer, so that the pointer still points to the memory location of the deallocated memory.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] The system may reallocate the previously freed memory, and if the program then dereferences the (now) dangling pointer, *unpredictable behavior may result*, as the memory may now contain completely different data.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] If the program writes to memory referenced by a dangling pointer, a silent corruption of unrelated data may result, leading to subtle bugs that can be extremely difficult to find.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] If the memory has been reallocated to another process, then attempting to dereference the dangling pointer can cause segmentation faults (UNIX, Linux) or general protection faults (Windows).
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] If the program has sufficient privileges to allow it to overwrite the bookkeeping data used by the kernel's memory allocator, the corruption can cause system instabilities.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] In object-oriented languages with garbage collection, dangling references are prevented by only destroying objects that are unreachable, meaning they do not have any incoming pointers; this is ensured either by tracing or reference counting.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] However, a finalizer may create new references to an object, requiring object resurrection to prevent a dangling reference.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Wild pointers, also called uninitialized pointers, arise when a pointer is used prior to initialization to some known state, which is possible in some programming languages.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] They show the same erratic behavior as dangling pointers, though they are less likely to stay undetected because many compilers will raise a warning at compile time if declared variables are accessed before being initialized.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] In many languages (e.g., the C programming language) deleting an object from memory explicitly or by destroying the stack frame on return does not alter associated pointers.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] The pointer still points to the same location in memory even though that location may now be used for other purposes.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] If the operating system is able to detect run-time references to null pointers, a solution to the above is to assign 0 (null) to dp immediately before the inner block is exited.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Another solution would be to somehow guarantee dp is not used again without further initialization.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Another frequent source of dangling pointers is a jumbled combination of `malloc()` and `free()` library calls: a pointer becomes dangling when the block of memory it points to is freed.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] As with the previous example one way to avoid this is to make sure to reset the pointer to null after freeing its reference—as demonstrated below.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] An all too common misstep is returning addresses of a stack-allocated local variable: once a called function returns, the space for these variables gets deallocated and technically they have "garbage values".
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Attempts to read from the pointer may still return the correct value (1234) for a while after calling `func`, but any functions called thereafter may overwrite the stack storage allocated for `num` with other values and the pointer would no longer work correctly.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] If a pointer to `num` must be returned, `num` must have scope beyond the function—it might be declared as `static`.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Antoni Kreczmar (1945–1996) has created a complete object management system which is free of dangling reference phenomenon.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] A similar approach was proposed by Fisher and LeBlanc under the name *Locks-and-keys*.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Wild pointers are created by omitting necessary initialization prior to first use.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Thus, strictly speaking, every pointer in programming languages which do not enforce initialization begins as a wild pointer.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] This most often occurs due to jumping over the initialization, not by omitting it.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Most compilers are able to warn about this.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Like buffer-overflow bugs, dangling/wild pointer bugs frequently become security holes.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] For example, if the pointer is used to make a virtual function call, a different address (possibly pointing at exploit code) may be called due to the vtable pointer being overwritten.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Alternatively, if the pointer is used for writing to memory, some other data structure may be corrupted.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Even if the memory is only read once the pointer becomes dangling, it can lead to information leaks (if interesting data is put in the next structure allocated there) or to privilege escalation (if the now-invalid memory is used in security checks).
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] When a dangling pointer is used after it has been freed without allocating a new chunk of memory to it, this becomes known as a "use after free" vulnerability.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] For example, CVE-2014-1776 is a use-after-free vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer 6 through 11 that was used by zero-day attacks by an advanced persistent threat.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] In C, the simplest technique is to implement an alternative version of the `free()` (or alike) function which guarantees the reset of the pointer.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] However, this technique will not clear other pointer variables which may contain a copy of the pointer.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] These uses can be masked through `#define` directives to construct useful macros (a common one being `#define XFREE(ptr) safeFree((void**)&(ptr))`), creating something like a metalanguage or can be embedded into a tool library apart.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] In every case, programmers using this technique should use the safe versions in every instance where `free()` would be used; failing in doing so leads again to the problem.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Also, this solution is limited to the scope of a single program or project, and should be properly documented.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Among more structured solutions, a popular technique to avoid dangling pointers in C++ is to use smart pointers.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] A smart pointer typically uses reference counting to reclaim objects.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Some other techniques include the tombstones method and the locks-and-keys method.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Another approach is to use the Boehm garbage collector, a conservative garbage collector that replaces standard memory allocation functions in C and C++ with a garbage collector.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] This approach completely eliminates dangling pointer errors by disabling frees, and reclaiming objects by garbage collection.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Another approach is to use a system such as CHERI, which stores pointers with additional metadata which may prevent invalid accesses by including lifetime information in pointers.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] CHERI typically requires support in the CPU to conduct these additional checks.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] In languages like Java, dangling pointers cannot occur because there is no mechanism to explicitly deallocate memory.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Rather, the garbage collector may deallocate memory, but only when the object is no longer reachable from any references.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] In the language Rust, the type system has been extended to include also the variables lifetimes and resource acquisition is initialization.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Unless one disables the features of the language, dangling pointers will be caught at compile time and reported as programming errors.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] To expose dangling pointer errors, one common programming technique is to set pointers to the null pointer or to an invalid address once the storage they point to has been released.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] When the null pointer is dereferenced (in most languages) the program will immediately terminate—there is no potential for data corruption or unpredictable behavior.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] This makes the underlying programming mistake easier to find and resolve.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] This technique does not help when there are multiple copies of the pointer.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Some debuggers will automatically overwrite and destroy data that has been freed, usually with a specific pattern, such as `0xDEADBEEF` (Microsoft's Visual C/C++ debugger, for example, uses `0xCC`, `0xCD` or `0xDD` depending on what has been freed).
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] This usually prevents the data from being reused by making it useless and also very prominent (the pattern serves to show the programmer that the memory has already been freed).
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Tools such as Polyspace, TotalView, Valgrind, Mudflap, AddressSanitizer, or tools based on LLVM can also be used to detect uses of dangling pointers.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] Other tools (SoftBound, Insure++, and CheckPointer) instrument the source code to collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity.
[src:memory-safety/dangling-pointer] The ARM64 memory tagging extension (MTE) - disabled by default on Linux systems, but can be enabled on Android 16 - triggers a segmentation fault when it detects use-after-free and buffer overflow.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] In computer science, **garbage collection** (**GC**) is a form of automatic memory management.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The *garbage collector* attempts to reclaim memory that was allocated by the program, but is no longer referenced; such memory is called *garbage*.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection was invented by American computer scientist John McCarthy around 1959 to simplify manual memory management in Lisp.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection relieves the programmer from doing manual memory management, where the programmer specifies what objects to de-allocate and return to the memory system and when to do so.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other, similar techniques include stack allocation, region inference, and memory ownership, and combinations thereof.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection may take a significant proportion of a program's total processing time, and affect performance as a result.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Resources other than memory, such as network sockets, database handles, windows, file descriptors, and device descriptors, are not typically handled by garbage collection, but rather by other methods (e.g. destructors).
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some such methods de-allocate memory also.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Many programming languages require garbage collection, either as part of the language specification (e.g., RPL, Java, C#, D, Go, and most scripting languages) or effectively for practical implementation (e.g., formal languages like lambda calculus).
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] These are said to be *garbage-collected languages*.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other languages, such as C and C++, were designed for use with manual memory management, but have garbage-collected implementations available.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some languages, like Ada, Modula-3, and C++/CLI, allow both garbage collection and manual memory management to co-exist in the same application by using separate heaps for collected and manually managed objects.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Still others, like D, are garbage-collected but allow the user to manually delete objects or even disable garbage collection entirely when speed is required.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although many languages integrate GC into their compiler and runtime system, *post-hoc* GC systems also exist, such as Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some of these *post-hoc* GC systems do not require recompilation.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC frees the programmer from manually de-allocating memory.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC uses computing resources to decide which memory to free.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Therefore, the penalty for the convenience of not annotating object lifetime manually in the source code is overhead, which can impair program performance.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] A peer-reviewed paper from 2005 concluded that GC needs five times the memory to compensate for this overhead and to perform as fast as the same program using idealized explicit memory management.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The comparison however is made to a program generated by inserting deallocation calls using an oracle, implemented by collecting traces from programs run under a profiler, and the program is only correct for one particular execution of the program.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Interaction with memory hierarchy effects can make this overhead intolerable in circumstances that are hard to predict or to detect in routine testing.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The impact on performance was given by Apple as a reason for not adopting garbage collection in iOS, despite it being the most desired feature.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The moment when the garbage is actually collected can be unpredictable, resulting in stalls (pauses to shift/free memory) scattered throughout a session.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unpredictable stalls can be unacceptable in real-time environments, in transaction processing, or in interactive programs.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors address these problems, with varying trade-offs.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Tracing garbage collection is the most common type of garbage collection, so much so that "garbage collection" often refers to tracing garbage collection, rather than other methods such as reference counting.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The overall strategy consists of determining which objects should be garbage collected by tracing which objects are *reachable* by a chain of references from certain root objects, and considering the rest as garbage and collecting them.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, there are a large number of algorithms used in implementation, with widely varying complexity and performance characteristics.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting garbage collection is where each object has a count of the number of references to it.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage is identified by having a reference count of zero.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] An object's reference count is incremented when a reference to it is created and decremented when a reference is destroyed.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] When the count reaches zero, the object's memory is reclaimed.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] If two or more objects refer to each other, they can create a cycle whereby neither will be collected as their mutual references never let their reference counts become zero.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] ) use specific cycle-detecting algorithms to deal with this issue.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] for the "backpointers" which create cycles.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Under reference counting, a weak reference is similar to a weak reference under a tracing garbage collector.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is a special reference object whose existence does not increment the reference count of the referent object.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] , rather than being permitted to remain dangling, meaning that it turns into a predictable value, such as a null reference.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting requires space to be allocated for each object to store its reference count.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The count may be stored adjacent to the object's memory or in a side table somewhere else, but in either case, every single reference-counted object requires additional storage for its reference count.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Memory space with the size of an unsigned pointer is commonly used for this task, meaning that 32 or 64 bits of reference count storage must be allocated for each object.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] to store the reference count in unused areas of the object's memory.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Often, an architecture does not actually allow programs to access the full range of memory addresses that could be stored in its native pointer size; a certain number of high bits in the address is either ignored or required to be zero.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] If an object reliably has a pointer at a certain location, the reference count can be stored in the unused bits of the pointer.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] , 19 unused bits of this class pointer are used to store the object's reference count.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] In naive implementations, each assignment of a reference and each reference falling out of scope often require modifications of one or more reference counters.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, in a common case when a reference is copied from an outer scope variable into an inner scope variable, such that the lifetime of the inner variable is bounded by the lifetime of the outer one, the reference incrementing can be eliminated.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The outer variable "owns" the reference.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] whose constructors, destructors, and assignment operators manage the references.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] A smart pointer can be passed by reference to a function, which avoids the need to copy-construct a new smart pointer (which would increase the reference count on entry into the function and decrease it on exit).
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Instead, the function receives a reference to the smart pointer which is produced inexpensively.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Deutsch-Bobrow method of reference counting capitalizes on the fact that most reference count updates are in fact generated by references stored in local variables.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] It ignores these references, only counting references in the heap, but before an object with reference count zero can be deleted, the system must verify with a scan of the stack and register that no other reference to it still exists.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Consider a pointer that in a given interval of the execution is updated several times.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] But most of these updates are redundant.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Levanoni and Petrank measured an elimination of more than 99% of the counter updates in typical Java benchmarks.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] , at least for any objects which are shared, or potentially shared among multiple threads.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Atomic operations are expensive on a multiprocessor, and even more expensive if they have to be emulated with software algorithms.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] can be used to eliminate all atomic operations from the write-barrier.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Counters are never updated by the program threads in the course of program execution.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] They are only modified by the collector which executes as a single additional thread with no synchronization.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] This method can be used as a stop-the-world mechanism for parallel programs, and also with a concurrent reference counting collector.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Naive implementations of reference counting do not generally provide real-time behavior, because any pointer assignment can potentially cause a number of objects bounded only by total allocated memory size to be recursively freed while the thread is unable to perform other work.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is possible to avoid this issue by delegating the freeing of unreferenced objects to other threads, at the cost of extra overhead.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Escape analysis is a compile-time technique that can convert heap allocations to stack allocations, thereby reducing the amount of garbage collection to be done.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] This analysis determines whether an object allocated inside a function is accessible outside of it.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] If a function-local allocation is found to be accessible to another function or thread, the allocation is said to "escape" and cannot be done on the stack.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Otherwise, the object may be allocated directly on the stack and released when the function returns, bypassing the heap and associated memory management costs.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generally speaking, higher-level programming languages are more likely to have garbage collection as a standard feature.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] In some languages lacking built-in garbage collection, it can be added through a library, as with the Boehm garbage collector for C and C++.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most functional programming languages, such as ML, Haskell, and APL, have garbage collection built in.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Lisp is especially notable as both the first functional programming language and the first language to introduce garbage collection.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other dynamic languages, such as Ruby and Julia (but not Perl 5 or PHP before version 5.3, which both use reference counting), JavaScript and ECMAScript also tend to use GC.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Object-oriented programming languages such as Smalltalk, ooRexx, RPL and Java usually provide integrated garbage collection.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Notable exceptions are C++ and Delphi, which have destructors.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC and Logo have often used garbage collection for variable-length data types, such as strings and lists, so as not to burden programmers with memory management details.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] On the Altair 8800, programs with many string variables and little string space could cause long pauses due to garbage collection.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Similarly the Applesoft BASIC interpreter's garbage collection algorithm repeatedly scans the string descriptors for the string having the highest address in order to compact it toward high memory, resulting in $O(n^{2})$ performance and pauses anywhere from a few seconds to a few minutes.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] A replacement garbage collector for Applesoft BASIC by Randy Wigginton identifies a group of strings in every pass over the heap, reducing collection time dramatically.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC.SYSTEM, released with ProDOS in 1983, provides a windowing garbage collector for BASIC that is many times faster.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] C has never offered official support for garbage collection.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] C++ added garbage collection support in C++11 to the standard library, however this was removed in C++23 due to no compilers implementing support for the feature.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The features that were part of this were related to pointer safety.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although garbage collection support in the standard library was removed, some garbage collectors such as Boehm garbage collector (for C and C++) can still be used.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Boehm GC uses mark-and-sweep garbage collection.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] It can also be used in leak detection mode, where memory management is still manual however leaks and double-free errors can be detected and reported.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Its use can be called from the header `<gc.h>`.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] One can still abstract away manual object destructions in C++ by using the "resource acquisition is initialization" (RAII) idiom and smart pointers.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::unique_ptr` ties lifetimes to ownership, while `std::shared_ptr` uses reference counting to determine lifetime.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::weak_ptr` can be used to obtain a pointer without increasing the reference count.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unlike garbage collection, RAII is deterministic.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] While the Objective-C traditionally had no garbage collection, with the release of OS X 10.5 in 2007 Apple introduced garbage collection for Objective-C 2.0, using an in-house developed runtime collector.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, with the 2012 release of OS X 10.8, garbage collection was deprecated in favor of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) that was introduced with OS X 10.7.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Furthermore, since May 2015 Apple even forbade the usage of garbage collection for new OS X applications in the App Store.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] For iOS, garbage collection has never been introduced due to problems in application responsivity and performance; instead, iOS uses ARC.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection is rarely used on embedded or real-time systems because of the usual need for very tight control over the use of limited resources.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, garbage collectors compatible with many limited environments have been developed.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Microsoft .NET Micro Framework, .NET nanoFramework and Java Platform, Micro Edition are embedded software platforms that, like their larger cousins, include garbage collection.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Compile-time garbage collection is a form of static analysis allowing memory to be reused and reclaimed based on invariants known during compilation.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] This form of garbage collection has been studied in the Mercury programming language, and it saw greater usage with the introduction of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) into Apple's ecosystem (iOS and OS X) in 2011.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors have been developed, for example by Henry Baker and by Henry Lieberman.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] In Baker's algorithm, the allocation is done in either half of a single region of memory.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] When it becomes half full, a garbage collection is performed which moves the live objects into the other half and the remaining objects are implicitly deallocated.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] The running program (the 'mutator') has to check that any object it references is in the correct half, and if not move it across, while a background task is finding all of the objects.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generational garbage collection schemes are based on the empirical observation that most objects die young.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] In generational garbage collection, two or more allocation regions (generations) are kept, which are kept separate based on the object's age.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] New objects are created in the "young" generation that is regularly collected, and when a generation is full, the objects that are still referenced from older regions are copied into the next oldest generation.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some high-level language computer architectures include hardware support for real-time garbage collection.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most implementations of real-time garbage collectors use tracing.
[src:memory-safety/garbage-collection-computer-science] Such real-time garbage collectors meet hard real-time constraints when used with a real-time operating system.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:memory-safety/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
